<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-748-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 748 816.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  August 14 1990 v4 n28 p85(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Congress hears Apple on ELF. (extremely low frequency emissionsfrom computer monitors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Webster, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (political activity).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     LobbyingComputer DesignMonitorsHealthElectromagnetic RadiationUnited States. CongressGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John WebsterandM;Washington -- Apple urged the government to play a greater role in settingstandards when it testified before Congress last month on reported healtheffects from extremely low frequency (ELF) monitor emissions.andM;The occasion was a hearing on House Bill HR4801, which calls for increasedfunds to explore connections between prolonged exposure to VDTs andabnormally high numbers of miscarriages, cancer and other medical problems.andM;At the hearing, David Nagel, Apple vice president of advanced technology,said that &quot;more attention should be given to the issue&quot; and suggested settingindustry standards limiting ELF emissions.andM;Nagel also said that Apple plans to adopt its own emissions standards and is&quot;prepared to contribute research money&quot; to government and private-sectororganizations studying the issue.andM;Nagel went on to recommend a &quot;consortium approach&quot; to researching the effectsof VDT exposure.andM;Apple's testimony before Congress occurred the same week it joinedrepresentatives of third-party monitor manufacturers in San Jose, Calif., ata forum to discuss emissions (see related story, previous page).andM;Both events come about a month after Apple posted an AppleLink memo statingits commitment to safe products and to further researching the issue.andP;  Inthat memo, Apple stated its belief that &quot;computer monitors are safe ...andP;  andevidence on the issue is so far inconclusive.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>